It seems you require an elucidation of the foundational tenets of this particular digital edifice. Very well. Don't expect a revelation; these are merely the scaffolding erected to prevent the whole thing from collapsing under the weight of human folly.

Here are the [shortcuts](/Wikipedia:Shortcut) you might find... efficient, if you're prone to such things:

*   WP:5[WP:5](/Wikipedia:5)
*   WP:5P[WP:5P](/Wikipedia:5P)
*   WP:PILLARS[WP:PILLARS](/Wikipedia:PILLARS)

The fundamental principles of [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia), in a desperate attempt to impose some semblance of order on a chaotic collaborative effort, may be summarized in five rather optimistic "pillars." Consider them less as unwavering commandments and more as polite suggestions whispered into the void of the internet.

## Wikipedia is an encyclopedia

This platform, despite all evidence to the contrary from certain contributors, is intended as an [encyclopedia](/Encyclopedia). It ambitiously attempts to combine the comprehensive reach of general [encyclopedias](/Encyclopedia) with the focused depth of specialized ones. Furthermore, it incorporates elements typically found in [almanacs](/Almanac)—those quaint repositories of facts and figures—and the geographical precision of [gazetteers](/Gazetteer).

However, and this is where the constant struggle manifests, [Wikipedia is not](/Wikipedia:NOT) a free-for-all. It is definitively not a [soapbox](/Wikipedia:SOAPBOX) for your latest manifesto or grievances, nor is it an [advertising platform](/Wikipedia:SPAM) for your dubious ventures. It decidedly eschews the superficiality of a [social network](/Wikipedia:NOTSOCIALNETWORK), the self-aggrandizing tendencies of a [vanity press](/Wikipedia:COI), or, perhaps most disappointingly to some, an experiment in pure [anarchy](/Wikipedia:NOTANARCHY) or unfettered [democracy](/Wikipedia:NOTDEMOCRACY). It is not designed to be an [indiscriminate collection of information](/Wikipedia:INDISCRIMINATE)—a digital attic for every stray thought or obscure data point—nor is it merely a web [directory](/Wikipedia:NOTDIRECTORY) pointing to other places.

Furthermore, it is distinct from a [dictionary](/Wikipedia:NOTDICT) (though it defines terms, its purpose is broader), a [newspaper](/Wikipedia:NOTNEWS) (it reports on established knowledge, not breaking events), an [instruction manual](/Wikipedia:NOTHOW) (it describes how things are, not how to do them), nor simply a collection of [source documents](/Wikipedia:NPS) or raw [media files](/Wikipedia:NOTGALLERY). While its [fellow Wikimedia projects](/Wikipedia:SIS) might fulfill some of these other functions, Wikipedia itself maintains a singular, often misunderstood, purpose: to compile verifiable, neutral knowledge. The distinction, though seemingly obvious, is one that requires constant reinforcement, as if the very nature of human desire pushes against such clear boundaries.

