## Wikipedia is written from a neutral point of view

Ah, neutrality. A concept as elusive as genuine altruism. We strive, with varying degrees of success, for [articles](/Encyclopedia) to adopt an impartial tone. The goal is to [document and explain major points of view](/Wikipedia:NPOV) on a given subject, rather than endorsing any one of them. This requires giving [due weight](/Wikipedia:DUE) to different perspectives based on their prominence in reliable sources, not on an editor's personal preference. We actively avoid [advocacy](/Wikipedia:ADVOCACY) of any kind; the task is to characterize information and issues, to describe them dispassionately, rather than to engage in debates within the article itself.

It's a rather simple directive, yet endlessly complex in practice. In certain, blessedly uncomplicated areas, a single, universally recognized point of view might suffice. In others, a multitude of perspectives clamor for attention. In such cases, our responsibility is to describe these multiple points of view accurately and within their proper context, presenting them as they are understood, rather than proclaiming any single one as "the truth" or "the best view"—a fool's errand in most matters of human discourse.

Crucially, all [articles](/Encyclopedia) must strive for [verifiable accuracy](/Wikipedia:V), supported by [citations](/Wikipedia:CS) drawn from [reliable sources](/Wikipedia:RS). This becomes particularly paramount when the topic is controversial, a magnet for impassioned, often unsubstantiated, claims, or when it concerns [a living person](/Wikipedia:BLP), whose reputation is directly at stake. There is no room here for editors' [personal experiences, interpretations, or opinions](/Wikipedia:OR); these are the raw materials of bias, and they do not belong on Wikipedia. If you want to share your unique worldview, I suggest a blog.

