## Wikipedia's editors should treat each other with respect and civility

And here we venture into the realm of the truly aspirational. Despite the inherent anonymity and the often-volatile nature of online interactions, editors are expected to [respect their fellow Wikipedians](/Wikipedia:CIV), even—perhaps especially—when fundamental disagreements arise. This means applying a basic level of Wikipedia [etiquette](/Wikipedia:EQ) and, crucially, refraining from engaging in [personal attacks](/Wikipedia:PA) or destructive [edit wars](/Wikipedia:EW). Such behavior only serves to degrade the environment and distract from the actual task at hand.

The expectation is to [seek consensus](/Wikipedia:CON) through discussion and reasoned argument, rather than by force or stubbornness. One must [never disrupt Wikipedia to illustrate a point](/Wikipedia:POINT); the project's stability and integrity outweigh any individual's desire to prove a philosophical or procedural stance. It is expected that editors will act in good faith, and, perhaps even more challenging, [assume good faith](/Wikipedia:AGF) on the part of others. This assumption, while often tested, is a necessary lubricant for collaboration.

A particular emphasis is placed on being open and [welcoming to newcomers](/Wikipedia:BITE). The project thrives on fresh perspectives, even if they arrive with a certain... naivety. Should conflicts inevitably arise—and they will, because humans are involved—the prescribed path is to discuss them calmly on the appropriate [talk pages](/H:TP), following established [dispute resolution procedures](/Wikipedia:DR). And, as a final, weary reminder: consider that there are 7,113,473 other articles on the English Wikipedia. Perhaps one of them holds more promise for improvement and less potential for conflict than the one currently consuming your attention. It's a vast, endless ocean of content; pick your battles wisely. Or don't. It's not my universe.

